+==== CSRs
+
+[[ACE-CSR-impl-ids]]
+===== `acevendorid`, `acearchid`, and `aceimpid`
+
+{empty}
+(((CSR, `acemvendorid`)))
+(((CSR, `acemarchid`)))
+(((CSR, `acemimpid`)))
+`acevendorid`, `acearchid`, and `aceimpid` identify the version of the ACE unit, analogously to `mvendorid`, `marchid`, `mimpid` CSRs for the hart.
+
+The `acemvendorid` CSR is a 32-bit read-only register providing the JEDEC manufacturer ID of the provider of the ACE unit (or 0 it is not commercial).
+
+The `acemarchid` CSR is a 32-bit read-only register encoding the base microarchitecture of the ACE unit. Non-commercial IDs are allocated globally by RVI, while commercial IDs are specific to the acemvendorid`
+
+The `acemimpid` CSR is a 32-bit read-only register that provides a unique encoding of the version of the ACE unit implementation. This register must be readable in any implementation, but a value of 0 can be returned to indicate that the field is not implemented. The Implementation value should reflect the design of the ACE unit itself and not any surrounding system.
+
+These three CSRs, together, form the _Implementation Qualifier_ (see <<ACE-extra-content>>).
+
+// ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
+
+[[ACE-CSR-acestart]]
+===== `acestart`
+
+{empty}
+(((CSR, `acestart`)))
+`acestart` is an alias for `vstart`. Therefore, it is an XLEN-bit RW CSR.
+ACE defines it also when the V extension is not enabled.
+
+`acestart` tracks the progress of resumable ACE instructions, such as `ace.load`, `ace.store`, `ace.input` and `ace.output`.
+
+Progress tracking by `acestart` also applies to `ace.exec` when iteratively processing a multi-block operand, as `ace.exec` may be interrupted between blocks.
+Only these instructions honor a nonzero `acestart`; all other instructions ignore it and are restarted, with `acestart` also being cleared.
+
+Since ACE does not have an _intrinsic_ concept of element length, `acestart` counts the number of _bits_ processed so far nu `ace.exec`, not the number of elements, or read/written by `ace.input`/`ace.output` and `ace.prov`/`ace.import`/`ace.export` or `ace.store`/`ace.load`.
+
+Hardware writes this register on interruption.
+Software may save and restore the register across context switches.
+For certain algorithms, writing zero to `acestart` to force a full restart of `ace.exec` may lead to inconsistent or unpredictable results.
+Writing an invalid or non-supported nonzero value raises an illegal instruction exception.
+
+When a vector instruction is interrupted, the CSR follows `vstart` semantics as expected, i.e., it counts the number of processed elements.
+When an ACE instruction is interrupted, the CSR follows the `acestart` semantics described here.
+
+[NOTE]
+====
+The reason `vstart` can be reused as `acestart` comes from the fact that the Risc-V ISA exposes a computation model in which the observable results are the same as if the instructions were executed in order.
+If an implementation has executed instructions past the PC when an interrupt occurs, those instructions are discarded and must be re‑executed upon return from the handler. Only the instruction at the PC may be interrupted in a way that it saves temporary state that allows it to be resumed later.
+There is no situation in which the microarchitecture of a hart can simultaneously interrupt multiple instructions allowing them to resume at the same time.
+Hence, `vstart` can safely be reused by ACE as `acestart`.
+====

 // ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

+[[ACE-CSR-acenonce]]
+===== `acenonce0` and `acenonce1`
+
+{empty}
+(((CSR, `acenonce`)))
+`acenonce0` and `acenonce1` are XLEN-bit URW CSR that define the nonce to be used in `ace.import` and `ace.export` (see <<ACE-export-import-algorithms>>).
+`acenonce0` contains bits [63:0] of the nonce, and `acenonce1` contains bits [95:64] of the nonce.
+The most significant 32 bits of `acenonce1` are fixed to zero.
+
+On RV32, 32-bit CSR `acenonce0h` shadows bits [63:32] of `acenonce0`, allowing these bits to be accessed.
+
+=== `Zlio`: ACE with support for `ace.input` and `ace.output`
+
+The `Zlio` base ACE extension contains all instructions in `Zlv` by replacing
+all vector registers with ACEIOBUF. `Zlio` and `Zlv` are mutually exclusive.
+`Zlio` adds two CSRs (`aceiobuftop`, `aceiobuflen`, and `acemaxiobuflen`), and
+two dedicated memory instructions (`ace.input` and `ace.output`).
+
+==== Instructions
+
+===== `ace.exec`
+
+Only Form D `ace.exec` is supported. See <<ACE-instruction-exec>> for the full
+`ace.exec` definition.
+
+===== `ace.setst`
+
+The vector form is replaced by ACEIOBUF. See <<ACE-instruction-setst>> for the
+full `ace.setst` definition.
+
+===== `ace.derive`
+
+The vector form is replaced by ACEIOBUF.  See <<ACE-instruction-derive>> for
+the full `ace.setst` definition.
